\cf0 02_Reference_Image:
\f0\b0  The icons I will be doing is a whole set. For this tutorial I'll walk you through a couple. The first icon is a 'PDA Device' so I need to know what a 'PDA Device' looks like. This image shows one of the more popular types, a 'BlackBerry'. I'll use this to base my icon on.\
\

\f2\b 03a_Building_Vectors, 03b_Building_Vectors, 03c_Building_Vectors:
\f0\b0  I start building my shapes in vector format. With icons you can build a lot of your content using basic shapes like circles, rectangles, rounded corner rectangles, ovals and squares. As seen with the blue outlined shapes I have two circles and two rectangles and from this I'll create the end shape I desire.\
\
Once I have all my core shapes built I am ready to start working out my color.\
\

\f2\b 04_Color_Scheme:
\f0\b0  I start laying in color picking up cues from my reference. Of course this is an icon so I am purposely over simplifying my art. Instead of a screen full of smaller icons I have one etc.\
\
I tend to work out my color scheme in flat colors and strokes of color. I'll then go back and add any blended FX and gradients at the next stage in my process.\
\

\f2\b 05_Glassy_FX:
\f0\b0  Some people prefer using the gradient tool to create blends but I find that too limiting and I want more control over my art so I use shape blending rather then the gradient tool. Besides if you look at the curved blend on the right you couldn't make the gradient tool follow that curve, you could get close but no cigar. So old school vector methods still work best from time to time.\
\
The pink outlined box shows the mask I'll put the blended shapes into. The gradient on the left is also a shape blend. You could do this one using a gradient it's personal preference. Another reason I use shape blends is I can dictate the amount of steps between the blend and this helps with doing GUI icons. Letting the computer interpolate a gradient sometimes brings about unwanted results but if you set the steps to match the iconic resolution you can avoid this. But that is a very technical aspect of GUI design so I'll leave it for another tutorial.\
\
You can see the other blended FX I have in the background of the screen that is in place already.\
