\f2\b \cf0 06_Detailing:
\f0\b0  This shows all the blended content in place and you can see how the icon really pops now. We've added detailing without adding complexity which is the key to iconic illustration. Detail is good but complexity is bad.\
\

\f2\b 07_Thicker_Outer_Line:
\f0\b0  Toggle between this image and the previous and you'll notice the thicker outer line. This added beefiness to the art really anchors it well and makes the icons work better at smaller sizes too. In general it's always good to have thinner inner lines and thicker outer lines. Your style however will be the ultimate indicator of when to do this though.\
\

\f2\b 08_Creating_Dropshadow, 09_Dropshadow_Blending:
\f0\b0  Once again I use shape blends rather then the gradient tool. The subtle shadow adds a nice dimension to the art now and offsets the icon from it's background.\
\

\f2\b 10_Final_PDA_Icon:
\f0\b0  My icon art for the 'PDA Device' is now complete.\
\

\f2\b 11_Building_Badge_Vectors:
\f0\b0  I'll walk you through one more icon. This one is for 'Security' unlike the previous icon this isn't a literal one. It's more of a conceptual icon. So I chose a visual metaphor to represent 'Security' that being a badge type of shield. The badge was easy to create, I just created half of it then flipped it and fused it together. The star was created using the star tool.\
\

\f2\b 12_Working_Out_Colors:
\f0\b0  Pretty standard colors for this icons. Gold and Silver. Note the style of a darker shade for the stroke and lighter shade for the fill.\
\

\f2\b 13_Building_Glassy_FX, 14_Masking_Glassy_FX:
\f0\b0  The first glassy FX I create is the gold star. For continuity sake I am using the same curved shape in all my icons to create the faux reflections. The pink outline shows the mask I'll apply to the blended shapes.\
\

\f2\b 15_Building_Glassy_FX2:
\f0\b0  The glassy FX on the shield itself is a little more complex. I wanted the shield to have a beveled look of sorts with a spine running down the middle. To accomplish this and give the illusion of a light source the glass FX had to be a darker shade on one side than the other. This meant using four blended shape parts instead of two. I then masked them into the pink outlined shape shown.\
\

\f2\b 16_Glassy_FX_Done:
\f0\b0  Most of the icon is done at this point. We just need to polish up the art and add some detailing.\
\

\f2\b 17_Thicker_Outer_Line:
\f0\b0  Toggle between the previous image and this one to see how I beefed up the outer line. As I said earlier, doing this really anchors it well and makes the icons work better at smaller sizes.\
\

\f2\b 18_Creating_Dropshadow, 19_Dropshadow_Blended:
\f0\b0  Even though all my icons will have drop-shadows they are not all identical. This one for example if you compare it to the PDA has a smaller inner circle it's blending from. This is because the PDA has a wider base then the badge icon. So it's the same method but adapted to work specifically with the art. This is important because one size never fits all when it comes to illustration.\
\

